{
  "q1_accurate": [
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.Address", "note": "composed_by gave the direct holder set with file:line (addrConn clientconn.go:1242, base.SubConnInfo, pickfirst.scData, AddressMapV2, http2Client) that I cited across §1-§7"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.Endpoint", "note": "composed_by located endpointsharding.ChildState, xdsresource.Endpoint, DNSUpdate, endpointData — the endpoint carriers in §6/§11"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.State", "note": "composed_by located rlsBalancer, delegatingResolver, priority.childBalancer, manual.Resolver, ccResolverWrapper, lazyBalancer, subBalancerWrapper holders in §1/§3/§9"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "balancer.SubConn", "note": "composed_by/inherited_by located grpclb cache, outlierdetection.subConnWrapper, clusterimpl.scWrapper, endpointWeight for §8/§10"},
    {"tool": "sense_search", "query": "xds resolver struct stores current config selector resolver state", "note": "pointed directly to xdsResolver at xds_resolver.go:226 whose xdsConfig field I cited in §3"},
    {"tool": "sense_search", "query": "ringhash balancer struct fields endpoint ring subConns map", "note": "surfaced ring/ringEntry/endpointState/endpointInfo so I could confirm §12 stores only derived hashKey/weight"}
  ],
  "q1_wrong": [
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "resolver.Address", "note": "retained_via_interfaces contained many spurious chains (e.g. grpc.serverStream > ... > http2Client > resolver.Address, orca.wrappedStream, opentelemetry.attachLabelsStream) that I had to discard after reading the actual structs; the note itself flagged them as unverified satisfiers"},
    {"tool": "sense_search", "query": "outlier detection balancer endpoint address map field holding endpointInfo", "note": "returned methods (removeSubConnFromEndpointMapEntry, unejectEndpoint) not the struct definition, so it did not directly locate the endpoints/addrs fields — I read the struct to get them"}
  ],
  "q2_fallbacks": [
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "resolver.Address / Endpoint / State / SubConn", "fallback": "read", "missing": "composed_by gives the struct's start line (line_start) but not the specific retaining FIELD line; the task required file:line of each field, so I read every holder struct to pin lines like scData.addr:157, addrConn.addrs:1263, outlierDetectionBalancer.endpoints:221"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "resolver.Address", "fallback": "read", "missing": "no way to distinguish a real containment field from a spurious interface-satisfier chain, forcing struct reads to verify each retained_via_interfaces row before citing"}
  ],
  "q3_hints": [],
  "q4_value": "The composed_by + retained_via_interfaces tree gave me the transitive, cross-package holder map in one call — including interface/nested carriers like xdsresource.Endpoint > Locality > EndpointsUpdate and the endpointsharding EndpointMap — that no single grep for 'Address' or 'Endpoint' would have surfaced, which is the exact easy-to-miss class the ticket warned about.",
  "q5_improve": "Have composed_by/retained_via_interfaces report the specific field name and its line within the holder struct (not just the struct's start line), and mark whether the containment is a concrete field vs an unverified interface-satisfier guess — that would have removed ~15 confirmatory Read calls and the manual pruning of bogus chains.",
  "score": 8,
  "score_rationale": "The composition graph handed me a transitive, interface-crossing holder map I could not have cheaply reconstructed with grep (Q1/Q4), but every citation still required a Read to pin the field line and I had to discard spurious blast chains (Q1_wrong/Q2), which is squarely the 7-8 'faster but still needed fallbacks' band."
}

